         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... of all companions beginning with ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the thinking concerning (urging/comfort?) completely ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... but the thinking concerning desire (of?) the own women ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... for me the monks [are] becoming ... in the manner of pupil. ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... suddenly; exactly like ... of the speculations ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... but the knowledge [is] the killer in order to hurt all ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... I did ... seeing the fear [triggered] by these ones; as the ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... trembled. The lord Māra indeed ... the big, violant [ob.sg]</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... I am able ... with (?) ... provided with strength, going away ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... and the world of which, the master precisely ... the women ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... was led from the king (of kings) Śuddhodana, ... marvellous[ly] ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... truely he did ... 8. The sound of the dr(um) ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (king) Śuddhodana ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the women ...</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="philcomment">The meter is unclear, but seems to consists (at least partly) of seven-syllable cola.</note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment">There are only two roots known ending in -<hi>rw</hi>: <hi>wārw<hi rend="superscript">ā</hi></hi>- "to urge oneself" and <hi>tsārw<hi rend="superscript">ā</hi></hi>- "to be comforted", so that one can either restore <hi>(wa)rw(ā)lyñeṣṣ</hi>e "pertaining to urging" or <hi>(tsa)rw(ā)lyñeṣṣe</hi> "pertaining to comforting".</note><note corresp="#a7" type="philcomment"><hi>ṣṣawa</hi> is no doubt the end of a 1.sg.act. Pt IV form.</note><note corresp="#b2" type="philcomment"><hi>yaukañ</hi> can hardly be a verbal form of <hi>yaukk<hi rend="superscript">ā</hi></hi>- "to use"; maybe this hapax is a causal of a noun <hi>yauk</hi>* or an adverb modifying <hi>yneñca</hi> "going".</note><note corresp="#b5" type="philcomment">The reading after the number is difficult, but the first akṣara quite clearly seems to be ‹ḍi›; since <hi>newe</hi> "roaring" is used with respect to the sound of drums in other passages, one may restore a form <hi>ḍiṇḍim</hi> from Skt. <hi>ḍiṇḍima</hi>- "a kind of drum; clamour".</note></p>
         </div>
